<Base title="A repeatable architecture for onboarding vendor APIs — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">platform</span>
  <h1>A repeatable architecture for onboarding vendor APIs</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Six-plus third-party integrations — Huawei FusionSolar, Solcast, GoodWe,
    Enedis, and more — each spanning six repositories. The deliverable wasn't any
    single integration; it was making the next one routine.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    A solar-monitoring platform lives or dies by ingestion: every logger vendor,
    inverter cloud, and grid operator exposes data differently. Each new vendor
    API must be fetched, normalized to the platform's canonical format,
    registered as a measurement system, scheduled, backed up, and exposed
    through the API contract — six repositories touched per integration, from
    Kotlin importers to PHP measurement systems to infrastructure config.
  </p>

  <h2>The platform, not the plumbing</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>A fixed onboarding path:</strong> importer → preprocessor →
      measurement-system registration → scheduling → backup → API spec → docs.
      Every integration is decomposed into the same repo-scoped steps, in the
      same order, reviewable independently. Planning a vendor became writing a
      checklist, not an adventure.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Self-recovery as a feature:</strong> the irradiance importer runs
      a daily completeness audit (per-system record counts) and automatically
      re-fetches gaps on the next cycle — self-healing within an hour, covering
      source-side outages, endpoint failures, and maintenance windows without a
      human in the loop.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Protecting the realtime SLA:</strong> when metrics showed bulk
      historical backfills slowing live ingestion, historical traffic moved to a
      dedicated account and lane for the largest partner on that API — bulk and
      realtime stopped competing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Session reuse at fleet scale:</strong> refactored the importer
      launcher to group jobs by credentials and reuse login sessions, cutting
      redundant authentication against vendor APIs (some of which rate-limit
      logins harder than data calls).
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Deciding what <em>not</em> to build</h2>
  <p>
    The same ownership included feasibility spikes — six-plus vendor APIs
    evaluated and sized before anyone committed. The most consequential one
    turned a stalled go/no-go on a national grid-operator integration into a
    concrete decision, by identifying that the only genuinely new component was
    one importer and one controller extension on top of the existing
    curtailment engine.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    The first integration you build is a feature; the second is a pattern; by
    the third, any step that isn't templated is a future incident. Invest in the
    checklist earlier.
  </p>
</Base>
